WeightIt

#install.packages("WeightIt")
library(WeightIt)

(Treatment variable) ~ (Covariates to be balanced) Details in method can be found in here : https://www.rdocumentation.org/packages/WeightIt/versions/0.2.0/topics/weightit

set.seed(1234)
logreg.ATT <- weightit(exposure1~male+white+age+susp+mathG+readG+parentED+housesmoke,
                       data=df,
                       method="ps",
                       estimand="ATT")
gbm.ATT <- weightit(exposure1~male+white+age+susp+mathG+readG+parentED+housesmoke,
                    data=df,
                    method="twang",
                    stop.method="ks.mean",
                    estimand="ATT")
names(logreg.ATT)

Cobalt (Covariate Balance Tables)

More descriptions on cobalt package are here : https://www.rdocumentation.org/packages/cobalt/versions/3.2.0.

#install.packages(cobalt)
library(cobalt)
logreg.balance <- bal.tab(logreg.ATT) # bal.tab = balance table
love.plot(logreg.balance, title="Covariate Balance (Logistic regression)")

gbm.balance <- bal.tab(gbm.ATT)
gbm.balance

# ids=~1 means no clusters.
# weights : sampling weights
design.ATT <- svydesign(ids=~1, weights=gbm.ATT$weights, data=df)
# svyglm() gits a generalized linear model to data from a complex surgey design, with inverse-probability weighting and design-based standard errors
glm.gbmweight <- svyglm(smoke1~exposure1,design=design.ATT,family=quasibinomial())
summary(glm.gbmweight)

#install.packages("MatchIt")
#install.packages("optmatch")
library(MatchIt)

##     lalonde
library(optmatch)
## The optmatch package has an academic license. Enter relaxinfo() for more information.
# full matching
match1 = matchit(exposure1~ male+white+age+susp+mathG+readG+parentED+housesmoke,
                       data=df,
                       method="full")
## Warning in optmatch::fullmatch(d, ...): Without 'data' argument the order of the match is not guaranteed
##     to be the same as your original data.
fullmatch.balance <- bal.tab(match1)
love.plot(fullmatch.balance, title="Covariate Balance (Full matching)")

matched1 <- match.data(match1)
